      <h1>Companies House identity verification: the complete guide for UK directors</h1>
      <p class="canonical"><strong>Question:</strong> How do I complete Companies House identity verification?</p>
      <p class="excerpt"><strong>Excerpt:</strong> Companies House identity verification is a mandatory process for all company directors, designed to combat fraud and increase transparency in the UK business environment.</p>
      <table class="meta">
        <tr><th>Slug</th><td>/learn/companies-house-identity-verification</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Applies to</th><td><span class="tag">ltd</span> <span class="tag">director</span></td></tr>
        <tr><th>Last reviewed</th><td>2026-05-27</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Reviewed by</th><td>—</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Next review due</th><td>—</td></tr>
      </table>

      <h2 class="section-h">Article body</h2>
      <div class="body">
        <h2>Why Companies House Identity Verification is Important</h2>
<p>Companies House is implementing new measures to improve the accuracy and reliability of the information held on the public register. Identity verification is a key part of this effort, aiming to prevent the misuse of companies for criminal activities like fraud and money laundering. By verifying the identity of directors, Companies House can ensure that the people listed as controlling companies are who they say they are. This helps to build trust and confidence in the UK business landscape.</p>
<h2>Who Needs to Verify Their Identity?</h2>
<p>All new and existing company directors of UK companies are required to verify their identity with Companies House. This includes directors of private limited companies, public limited companies (PLCs), and other company types registered in the UK. The requirement applies to every individual appointed as a director, regardless of their nationality or country of residence.</p>
<p>It's important to note that this verification is for <em>individuals</em> in director roles. Other company officers, such as company secretaries, are not currently subject to the same mandatory identity verification process, unless they also hold a director role.</p>
<h2>The Identity Verification Process</h2>
<p>Companies House offers two main ways to verify your identity: directly through their online service or through an authorised third-party agent. Most small business owners will use the direct online service.</p>
<h3>What you'll need</h3>
<p>Before you start, gather the following:</p>
<ul><li><strong>A valid email address:</strong> This will be used for communication and to set up your Companies House account.</li><li><strong>A UK mobile phone number:</strong> For security checks and two-factor authentication.</li><li><strong>Your UK driving licence or UK passport:</strong> These are the primary forms of identification accepted for the digital verification process. Make sure they are current and not expired.</li><li><strong>A device with a camera:</strong> You'll need a smartphone, tablet, or computer with a webcam to take a photo of your ID and a 'liveness' selfie during the process.</li><li><strong>Your National Insurance number:</strong> This helps Companies House link your identity to your records.</li></ul>
<h3>Step-by-step guide</h3>
<p>The process is generally straightforward and can be completed online:</p>
<ol><li><strong>Create a Companies House account:</strong> If you don't already have one, you'll need to register for a Companies House account. This involves providing your email address and setting up a password.</li><li><strong>Access the identity verification service:</strong> Once logged in, navigate to the identity verification section. You'll usually find a prompt or link to start the process.</li><li><strong>Choose your verification method:</strong> Select the direct online verification method.</li><li><strong>Enter your personal details:</strong> Provide your full name, date of birth, and National Insurance number.</li><li><strong>Scan your ID:</strong> You will be prompted to use your device's camera to scan your UK driving licence or UK passport. Follow the on-screen instructions carefully to ensure a clear scan.</li><li><strong>Take a 'liveness' selfie:</strong> The system will ask you to take a selfie to match your face to your ID document. This often involves moving your head slightly or blinking to prove you are a live person.</li><li><strong>Confirm and submit:</strong> Review all the information you've provided. Once you're satisfied, submit your verification request.</li><li><strong>Receive confirmation:</strong> Companies House will process your application and send you an email confirmation once your identity has been successfully verified. This can take a few days.</li></ol>
<h2>Deadlines and What Happens if You Don't Verify</h2>
<p>There isn't a single, universal deadline for all existing directors, as the implementation is being phased in. However, new directors appointed after the relevant legislation came into force must verify their identity. Companies House will communicate directly with companies and directors regarding specific deadlines for existing appointments.</p>
<p>Failing to verify your identity when required can lead to serious consequences. Companies House has powers to take enforcement action, which could include:</p>
<ul><li><strong>Financial penalties:</strong> Fines may be issued to directors who do not comply.</li><li><strong>Prosecution:</strong> In more severe cases, directors could face prosecution.</li><li><strong>Company strike-off:</strong> Ultimately, persistent non-compliance could lead to the company being struck off the register, meaning it ceases to legally exist.</li></ul>
<p>It's crucial to respond promptly to any communication from Companies House regarding identity verification to avoid these issues.</p>
<h2>Common mistakes</h2>
<ul><li><strong>Using expired ID:</strong> Ensure your passport or driving licence is valid and in date.</li><li><strong>Poor quality scans/photos:</strong> Blurry images of your ID or unclear selfies can lead to rejection and delays.</li><li><strong>Incorrect personal details:</strong> Double-check your name, date of birth, and National Insurance number match your official records.</li><li><strong>Ignoring Companies House communications:</strong> Don't dismiss emails or letters about verification; they contain important deadlines and instructions.</li><li><strong>Assuming someone else will do it:</strong> Identity verification is a personal responsibility for each director.</li></ul>
<div class="embed"><h3>Frequently asked questions</h3><p><strong>Q. Is Companies House ID verification still required if the company is closing?</strong><br>A. Yes, if you are a director of a company that is in the process of being dissolved or struck off, you are still required to complete identity verification if you receive a request from Companies House. Your obligations as a director continue until the company is officially removed from the register.</p><p><strong>Q. What documents can I use for identity verification?</strong><br>A. For the online verification service, you will primarily need a valid UK driving licence or a UK passport. Other forms of ID are generally not accepted through the digital process.</p><p><strong>Q. How long does Companies House identity verification take?</strong><br>A. The online process itself usually takes less than 15 minutes to complete. However, Companies House may take a few days to process and confirm your verification. You will receive an email once it's complete.</p><p><strong>Q. Can my accountant complete the verification for me?</strong><br>A. No, identity verification is a personal process that you, as the director, must complete yourself. Your accountant or agent cannot complete the 'liveness' check or scan your personal ID documents on your behalf. They can, however, guide you through the process and help ensure you have all the necessary information.</p><p><strong>Q. What if I don't have a UK address?</strong><br>A. If you are a director without a UK residential address, you will still need to verify your identity. Companies House provides guidance for overseas directors, which may involve different verification methods or specific documents. It's best to check the official Companies House guidance for non-UK residents.</p><p><strong>Q. What if I don't have a UK driving licence or passport?</strong><br>A. If you do not possess a valid UK driving licence or UK passport, you may need to use an alternative verification route, such as through an authorised agent. Companies House provides details on these alternative methods on their website.</p></div>
<h2>Sources &amp; references</h2>
