<section class="article" id="article-42">
      <div class="meta-bar">
        <span class="badge draft">DRAFT</span>
        <span class="topic">Self-Assessment</span>
      </div>
      <h1>Self-Assessment tax refunds: when and how you'll get yours</h1>
      <p class="canonical"><strong>Question:</strong> When and how will I receive my Self-Assessment tax refund?</p>
      <p class="excerpt"><strong>Excerpt:</strong> If you've overpaid tax through Self-Assessment, HMRC will typically refund the money directly to your bank account, or offset it against future tax bills, usually within 2-4 weeks for online returns.</p>
      <table class="meta">
        <tr><th>Slug</th><td>/learn/self-assessment-tax-refunds</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Applies to</th><td><span class="tag">sole-trader</span> <span class="tag">landlord</span> <span class="tag">contractor</span> <span class="tag">ltd</span></td></tr>
        <tr><th>Last reviewed</th><td>— (not yet reviewed)</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Reviewed by</th><td>—</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Next review due</th><td>—</td></tr>
      </table>

      <h2 class="section-h">Article body</h2>
      <div class="body">
        <h2>How you'll receive your refund</h2>
<p>When HMRC determines you're due a Self-Assessment tax refund, there are a few ways you might receive the money. The most common and quickest method is a direct bank transfer.</p>
<ul><li><strong>Direct to your bank account:</strong> If you filed your Self-Assessment tax return online and provided your bank details, HMRC will usually pay the refund directly into that account. This is the fastest way to get your money.</li><li><strong>Offset against future tax bills:</strong> If you have other outstanding tax liabilities, such as payments on account for the current tax year, HMRC may automatically use your refund to reduce these future payments. This means you might not receive a cash refund, but your next tax bill will be lower.</li><li><strong>Cheque:</strong> In some cases, particularly if HMRC doesn't have your bank details or if you specifically request it, a cheque might be issued. This method takes significantly longer than a direct bank transfer.</li></ul>
<h2>When to expect your refund</h2>
<p>The timeframe for receiving a Self-Assessment tax refund can vary, but HMRC aims for efficiency, especially for online submissions.</p>
<ul><li><strong>Online Self-Assessment returns:</strong> For straightforward online returns, HMRC typically processes refunds within 2 to 4 weeks. Some online claims may even be completed within 5 to 10 working days.</li><li><strong>Complex returns or security checks:</strong> If your return is more complex or HMRC needs to conduct additional security checks, the process can take longer, potentially up to 8 weeks or more.</li><li><strong>Paper returns:</strong> If you filed a paper Self-Assessment tax return, expect a longer wait. These can take 6 to 8 weeks, and sometimes up to 12 weeks, due to manual processing.</li></ul>
<p>It's worth noting that these are general timescales, and actual processing times can be affected by HMRC's workload, especially during peak periods like the end of the tax year (5 April) or after the 31 January Self-Assessment deadline.</p>
<h2>Checking the status of your refund</h2>
<p>You can easily check the status of your Self-Assessment tax refund online.</p>
<ol><li><strong>Log in to your HMRC online account:</strong> Access your personal tax account via the GOV.UK website.</li><li><strong>Navigate to the 'Self Assessment' section:</strong> Once logged in, find the Self Assessment area.</li><li><strong>Check 'Payments and Repayments':</strong> Look for details on your refund in this section.</li><li><strong>Use the HMRC app:</strong> You can also use the HMRC app to view your Self Assessment status, including any repayment updates.</li></ol>
<p>If your refund status shows as 'pending', it means HMRC has acknowledged your request and is processing it, but the payment hasn't been finalised or sent yet.</p>
<h2>Reasons for delays or unexpected amounts</h2>
<p>Several factors can lead to delays in receiving your refund or an amount different from what you expected:</p>
<ul><li><strong>Verification checks:</strong> HMRC may need to verify details like your bank information to prevent fraud.</li><li><strong>Missing or incorrect information:</strong> Errors or omissions on your tax return can cause delays as HMRC may need to contact you for clarification.</li><li><strong>Outstanding tax liabilities:</strong> As mentioned, your refund might be used to cover other tax debts, meaning you receive a smaller cash refund or none at all.</li><li><strong>Complex tax affairs:</strong> If your tax situation is complicated, it naturally takes HMRC longer to review and process.</li><li><strong>Busy periods:</strong> HMRC's processing times can increase during peak periods, such as after the 31 January Self-Assessment deadline.</li></ul>
<h2>Common mistakes</h2>
<ul><li><strong>Not providing bank details:</strong> Failing to provide up-to-date bank details can lead to delays or receiving a cheque instead of a quicker direct transfer.</li><li><strong>Incorrectly calculating tax:</strong> Mistakes in your income or expense calculations can result in an incorrect refund amount or even a tax bill.</li><li><strong>Not claiming all eligible reliefs:</strong> Missing out on tax reliefs or allowances means you might not be claiming the full refund you're due.</li><li><strong>Filing a paper return unnecessarily:</strong> Online filing is generally much faster for refunds.</li><li><strong>Contacting HMRC too soon:</strong> While frustrating, contacting HMRC before the typical processing times have passed may not speed up your refund. It's usually best to wait 4 to 6 weeks for online claims or 8 to 12 weeks for postal submissions before chasing.</li></ul>
<div class="embed"><h3>Frequently asked questions</h3><p><strong>Q. Can HMRC automatically refund overpaid taxes?</strong><br>A. Yes, in many cases, especially for PAYE (Pay As You Earn) overpayments, HMRC can automatically refund overpaid taxes. For Self-Assessment, once your return is processed and a refund is due, it's typically paid automatically to your nominated bank account.</p><p><strong>Q. How far back can I claim a tax refund?</strong><br>A. You generally have four years from the end of the tax year in which the overpayment occurred to claim a refund. For example, for the 2025/26 tax year (which ended 5 April 2026), you would typically have until 5 April 2030 to claim a refund.</p><p><strong>Q. What does 'Self Assessment repayment pending' mean?</strong><br>A. This status indicates that HMRC has received your refund request and is currently processing it. It's a normal part of the process and means your refund is on its way, though it hasn't been finalised or paid out yet.</p><p><strong>Q. Can I choose to have my refund offset against my next tax bill?</strong><br>A. Yes, if you have future tax liabilities, such as payments on account, HMRC may automatically use your refund to reduce these. You can also sometimes request this if you prefer not to receive a cash refund.</p><p><strong>Q. What if I don't receive my refund within the expected timeframe?</strong><br>A. If you've waited longer than the typical processing times (e.g., 4-6 weeks for online or 8-12 weeks for paper) and your online account shows no update, you can contact HMRC's Self-Assessment helpline or use their webchat service for an update.</p><p><strong>Q. Do I get interest on a delayed tax refund?</strong><br>A. HMRC may pay interest on overpaid tax, but specific rules and rates apply. This usually happens if the refund is significantly delayed due to HMRC's error.</p></div>
<h2>Sources &amp; references</h2>
<p>This draft was grounded against the following pages. An accountant should verify each cited figure before publishing.</p>
<ul><li>www.gov.uk — https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHi45RgSx1NE7pmW4deyKw1da3HTX00Uif_3T9vV7tjTggNpA5nCdfpM-S9orLW3lH2hB07LNK6K0kPhGjmnwtVK5fKe-uju5pb-diLZd1Tvjf8P8WjBlWk9wnSiKQieVtiaAYLZX0eocu3SPEcKbUfURT5I3tOVcMLSTgn9-rS</li><li>www.gov.uk — https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH8fz2E3hDlej1faarEdSVs2lzTEb95a2BffwaD8JtiQsvBIPJPh57FW3uihPZDc1Ls2a-FVYO2Efg8wQ9DU1eHgVVEhdNogjEvSlOWlmgVbpP1hLnR9WLe-Qw9c47Nzx9O0ZJfH86OQitCWkZiNCuflBcpsEbE3JnOz6bG39BytqPtDp_jljr7hPL34kWr</li><li>julianhobbs.com — https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHL-u5ojMo7-eBeAM7y9u3Kl9hwRzVFjMUUPVhi0gt6pVYnzQwbNFzQDM1TNFwjkzhphRttrW5RmWlyNN0nx0nvYP4gdzd-LpeFUL<em>uRc3RvgZwwLi1M1c6MmgBb</em>r_lOozGt13hNsD9AdYP9at4uB7FA6yRa4l7w==</li><li>riftrefunds.co.uk — https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQGJfXjYaZye88sMW0jtmRSd<em>FK1v-aZpLGIOWsXSJaM</em>KByH1qx03mw37dt2bGyjQBQoWACzjXPAA5Nmz2TbKd_ijhP33Kfcv3iuARQk1wsLAwvrh0vGiQDRTE7l7gpc1jTNv3c61scXXmGG1jiH1hzOiw-oZbGOx2ohvDOJlR9RuStZeEh7Z4=</li><li>sterlingandwells.com — https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHwKIXHbuyZs6FgiBn7LAp38A7rIo40llsY1XsCEJEvgSq-ZOgiQ7jQsK4Cjbk1rh68TuJLcnS9Ga6CF8oImnXEGDf2VmY08QnRL9alD97qBYC-mChjzytiYIh6vNMrXBYM88gh1<em>xCLD</em>njjd-6EdiRMqFQOohfXU1172unS9lDvE=</li><li>litrg.org.uk — https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHi4lACeVL62PCCzg2zuNb<em>yIP10gqX9UYapDR-T1SYPesCpGNmcFedOnOpmtDIrY9Un</em>9BhgoizfEulvvYUK_Vz-lOJWW-Ajb54a5jDPdTRJcI8xrZTx0Xt3fXs4rYmzXDLrRUi5kEvkzV67Bo0jeUn6VJyBTN3MBp</li><li>evaccountants.com — https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFQUUupAA8zJxI0JfaFnad2pZ<em>tkrLqdzibzHY</em>-YT391n6rCNmEFbsl1btfmWxa3dZicEWU8Cj2yMRwoxVgl6kIl2<em>Efcpy-0Z0ktHNw-77wVLggKub4RWMoi4p-uiIMVz0LJTTES7kHpTJce4E4776Fr0U</em>x9nB3DkTI=</li><li>theonlineaccountants.uk — https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFShEeHNvPIaY-zwHgnVyasVL0eZm0hvpcpIEdwzYPuB1QsbZekXDs9_<em>eYhYGs1g5QMGo39bmwga4hNgPli4Vh2dG-X-CxTjb-qTaer1vyXiIsMNcz63MCfhMKOrbg0beIqvw-lgm0qnm4xj6QsppVTG1x6mtYhv7YUTANCzoPD8HU</em>d5Q2BL_-2Z1W52gVyLzwvRs-zAkSiNMWg==</li><li>crunch.co.uk — https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFdGmkn89BJyY2h3raQqdiPpZbvZlrLYaNRvDc1SGr51MGtfrhDI_cjAX20uJ-DkTmQGcVvH7VPCpUH8WQKkpTxmJT9Hn-aB1EhMOVFptJLodhU0oVtNfk9fslQqVNQRaZ1whX-cxa5kbwvKUoSU-pTq2WnaWHDGuNoRbn36Emvs6VvgmyQ</li><li>severnaccounting.co.uk — https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHpApHbhq4bW8JD<em>jkCEHelEMe-wwbt-Le5YZ34FLuZ2UJ2JfAXYyFIxwRnoPs5EIotHstNqulNzFVQkAAqjDVDproiAVmzOZ4HEvLcWFQX03cHoymzQ1YrJzG4xOsJ5JQeLnEkYmgIc</em>8kk13Ji05CDuYAjpahXRGZx-uC7MOGfdIzkrnn</li></ul>
