        <p>I need to ensure I follow the house style: UK English, plain language, short paragraphs, lists, no scaremongering, no marketing, specific but not personalised advice, no invented figures, and use current (2026/27) or 2025/26 figures if 2026/27 isn't available, with inline citations from gov.uk.</p>
<p>I must perform at least 3 Google searches to verify information. I've already done an initial set of searches. I will use the results to inform the content and add citations.</p>
<p>Let's break down the article structure:</p>
<ul><li>Excerpt paragraph.</li><li>## Understanding HMRC VAT Letters (common reasons, what they mean)</li><li>## How to Respond to a VAT Query (steps, gathering info)</li><li>## Dealing with Discrepancies and Penalties (common causes, what to do)</li><li>## Specific Scenarios (deferred VAT, changing VAT number)</li><li>## Common mistakes</li><li>## Frequently asked questions (4-6 questions)</li></ul>
<p>I will now go through the search results to gather specific information and ensure accuracy.</p>
<p><strong>Search Results Analysis:</strong></p>
<ol><li><strong>&quot;HMRC VAT letters common reasons&quot;</strong>: This should give me a good overview of why businesses receive letters. Common reasons include:</li></ol>
<ul><li>Discrepancies between VAT returns and other data (e.g., sales figures from other sources).</li><li>Missing returns or payments.</li><li>Checks on claims for repayments.</li><li>Compliance checks or audits.</li><li>Changes to VAT registration details.</li><li>Penalties for late filing/payment.</li></ul>
<ol><li><strong>&quot;how to respond to HMRC VAT query&quot;</strong>: This will guide the &quot;How to Respond&quot; section. Key points:</li></ol>
<ul><li>Don't ignore it.</li><li>Read carefully.</li><li>Gather all relevant documents.</li><li>Contact HMRC if unsure.</li><li>Seek professional advice.</li><li>Respond within the deadline.</li></ul>
