<section class="article" id="article-49">
      <div class="meta-bar">
        <span class="badge draft">DRAFT</span>
        <span class="topic">VAT</span>
      </div>
      <h1>VAT Flat Rate Scheme: pros, cons and when to use it</h1>
      <p class="canonical"><strong>Question:</strong> What is the VAT Flat Rate Scheme and should I use it?</p>
      <p class="excerpt"><strong>Excerpt:</strong> The VAT Flat Rate Scheme (FRS) simplifies how small businesses handle VAT by allowing you to pay a fixed percentage of your gross turnover to HMRC, rather than calculating VAT on every sale and purchase.</p>
      <table class="meta">
        <tr><th>Slug</th><td>/learn/vat-flat-rate-scheme</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Applies to</th><td><span class="tag">ltd</span> <span class="tag">sole-trader</span> <span class="tag">contractor</span></td></tr>
        <tr><th>Last reviewed</th><td>— (not yet reviewed)</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Reviewed by</th><td>—</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Next review due</th><td>—</td></tr>
      </table>

      <h2 class="section-h">Article body</h2>
      <div class="body">
        <h2>What is the VAT Flat Rate Scheme?</h2>
<p>The VAT Flat Rate Scheme (FRS) is a simplified accounting method for VAT-registered small businesses. Instead of tracking the VAT you charge on sales (output VAT) and the VAT you pay on purchases (input VAT), you pay a single, fixed percentage of your total VAT-inclusive turnover to HMRC.</p>
<p>This scheme aims to reduce the administrative burden of VAT for smaller businesses. You still charge your customers the standard VAT rate (currently 20% for most goods and services). However, the amount you pay to HMRC is calculated using a lower, sector-specific flat rate percentage applied to your gross sales.</p>
<h2>How does the Flat Rate Scheme work?</h2>
<p>Under the FRS, the process is streamlined:</p>
<ol><li><strong>Charge VAT as normal</strong>: You continue to charge your customers VAT at the standard rate (e.g., 20%) on your invoices.</li><li><strong>Calculate gross turnover</strong>: At the end of your VAT period (usually quarterly), you total your gross turnover. This is your total sales figure, including the VAT you charged.</li><li><strong>Apply your flat rate</strong>: You then apply your specific flat rate percentage (which depends on your business sector) to this gross turnover. This is the amount you pay to HMRC.</li><li><strong>Keep the difference</strong>: The difference between the VAT you collected from customers and the lower flat rate amount you pay to HMRC is retained by your business. This difference is intended to cover the input VAT you would normally reclaim on your purchases.</li></ol>
<p><strong>Example:</strong> If your flat rate is 10% and you invoice a client £1,200 (which is £1,000 plus £200 VAT), you would pay HMRC 10% of £1,200, which is £120. You keep the remaining £80 from the VAT collected.</p>
<p><strong>First-year discount:</strong> If you are in your first year of VAT registration, you receive a 1% reduction on your flat rate percentage. So, if your sector rate is 14.5%, you would pay 13.5% during your initial 12 months of VAT registration.</p>
<p><strong>Input VAT (purchases):</strong> A key difference from standard VAT accounting is that you generally <strong>cannot reclaim VAT on most purchases</strong> under the FRS. The flat rate percentage is set lower to account for this. The main exception is for single purchases of capital expenditure goods costing £2,000 or more (including VAT), where you <em>can</em> reclaim the VAT.</p>
<h2>Who can use the Flat Rate Scheme?</h2>
<p>The FRS is designed for smaller businesses. To join, your business must meet specific criteria:</p>
<ul><li><strong>VAT-registered</strong>: You must already be registered for VAT, or be applying for VAT registration at the same time. The mandatory VAT registration threshold for 2026/27 is £90,000 of taxable turnover in any rolling 12-month period.</li><li><strong>Expected turnover</strong>: Your VAT-taxable turnover (excluding VAT) must be £150,000 or less in the next 12 months.</li><li><strong>Previous FRS use</strong>: You must not have left the FRS in the previous 12 months.</li><li><strong>No VAT offences</strong>: You must not have committed a VAT offence in the previous 12 months.</li><li><strong>Not associated with other FRS businesses</strong>: You must not be closely associated with another business already using the FRS.</li></ul>
<p>You must leave the scheme if your total business income (including VAT) exceeds £230,000 in any 12-month period, or if you expect it to exceed this amount in the next 30 days alone.</p>
<p><strong>Limited Cost Businesses:</strong> A crucial rule introduced in April 2017 is for &quot;limited cost businesses&quot;. You are considered a limited cost business if your spending on 'relevant goods' (excluding capital expenditure, food, drink, and vehicles) is either:</p>
<ul><li>Less than 2% of your gross turnover (including VAT).</li><li>Or, if it's more than 2% but less than £1,000 per year (or £250 per quarter for quarterly returns).</li></ul>
<p>If your business is classified as a limited cost business, you must use a flat rate of <strong>16.5%</strong>, regardless of your trade sector. This significantly reduces the financial benefit for many service-based businesses with low costs.</p>
<h2>Pros and Cons of the Flat Rate Scheme</h2>
<p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
<ul><li><strong>Simplified administration</strong>: Less record-keeping as you don't need to track VAT on every individual purchase.</li><li><strong>Predictable VAT payments</strong>: Payments are a fixed percentage of your gross turnover, making budgeting easier.</li><li><strong>Potential financial benefit</strong>: If your business has low VATable expenses and you are not a limited cost business, you may pay less VAT to HMRC than under the standard scheme.</li><li><strong>Cash accounting</strong>: The FRS can be used on a cash-based method, meaning you only pay VAT to HMRC on sales you've actually been paid for, which can help cash flow.</li></ul>
<p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
<ul><li><strong>Cannot reclaim most input VAT</strong>: You generally cannot reclaim VAT on your business purchases, which can be a significant disadvantage for businesses with high VATable costs (e.g., retail, manufacturing).</li><li><strong>Limited cost business rule</strong>: If you fall under the limited cost business definition, the 16.5% rate often makes the FRS less financially beneficial than standard VAT accounting.</li><li><strong>Less flexibility</strong>: You apply a single rate to all your sales, even if some are zero-rated or exempt, which can sometimes lead to paying more VAT.</li><li><strong>Exit thresholds</strong>: You must leave the scheme if your gross turnover exceeds £230,000, meaning you might need to switch schemes as your business grows.</li></ul>
<h2>Switching to and from the Flat Rate Scheme</h2>
<p><strong>Joining the FRS:</strong> You can apply to join the FRS online through your HMRC VAT account or by completing form VAT600 FRS. HMRC will confirm your start date in writing.</p>
<p><strong>Leaving the FRS:</strong> You can choose to leave the FRS voluntarily at any time, typically at the end of a VAT accounting period. You must inform HMRC in writing or via your Government Gateway account.</p>
<p>You are <strong>required to leave</strong> the scheme if:</p>
<ul><li>Your total business income (including VAT) exceeds £230,000 in any 12-month period.</li><li>HMRC notifies you that you are no longer eligible.</li><li>You are convicted of a VAT offence.</li></ul>
<p>After leaving, you must wait at least 12 months before you can rejoin the scheme.</p>
<h2>Common mistakes</h2>
<ul><li><strong>Not checking the &quot;limited cost business&quot; rule</strong>: Many service-based businesses assume the FRS is always beneficial, but the 16.5% rate for limited cost businesses often makes standard VAT accounting more cost-effective.</li><li><strong>Forgetting the 1% first-year discount</strong>: New VAT-registered businesses get a 1% discount on their flat rate for the first 12 months, which can impact calculations.</li><li><strong>Incorrectly reclaiming input VAT</strong>: Under the FRS, you generally cannot reclaim VAT on purchases, except for capital assets over £2,000 (including VAT). Attempting to reclaim VAT on everyday expenses is a common error.</li><li><strong>Not monitoring turnover</strong>: Failing to track your gross turnover can lead to exceeding the £230,000 exit threshold without realising, resulting in non-compliance.</li></ul>
<div class="embed"><h3>Frequently asked questions</h3><p><strong>Q. Is it simple to change the VAT from the Flat Rate Scheme?</strong><br>A. Yes, changing from the Flat Rate Scheme is relatively straightforward. You can leave voluntarily at the end of any VAT accounting period by notifying HMRC in writing or through your online VAT account. You will then switch to standard VAT accounting.</p><p><strong>Q. Can you confirm if this VAT return uses the new Flat Rate Scheme?</strong><br>A. Your VAT return will specify which scheme you are using. If you have applied and been approved for the Flat Rate Scheme, your VAT calculations will be based on applying your specific flat rate percentage to your gross turnover, rather than deducting input VAT from output VAT. Your accountant can confirm the specifics for your business.</p><p><strong>Q. How do I set up the option to pay VAT from FreeAgent?</strong><br>A. FreeAgent, like other accounting software, can be configured to handle VAT under the Flat Rate Scheme. You typically need to select the FRS option in your VAT settings and enter your specific flat rate percentage. The software will then calculate your VAT liability accordingly. You should consult FreeAgent's help guides or your accountant for precise setup instructions.</p><p><strong>Q. What is the process for switching to the VAT Flat Rate Scheme?</strong><br>A. To switch to the FRS, you must first be VAT registered and meet the eligibility criteria, particularly that your expected VAT-exclusive turnover in the next 12 months is £150,000 or less. You apply to HMRC online via your VAT account or by submitting form VAT600 FRS. HMRC will then confirm your start date.</p><p><strong>Q. What are the invoice notes for different VAT schemes? Do suppliers need to include a VAT number?</strong><br>A. When you are VAT registered, regardless of the scheme, you must issue VAT-compliant invoices to your customers. These invoices should clearly show your VAT registration number, the VAT rate applied (usually 20%), and the total VAT charged. Your suppliers, if they are VAT registered, must also include their VAT number on their invoices to you. The VAT scheme you use (FRS or standard) affects how you calculate what you pay to HMRC, not what you charge customers or what your suppliers charge you.</p></div>
